Assignee: Unassigned
Signals: Security, Validated, Patch generated, Attack-path

# Summary
Introduced: the tabbed settings UI hides security-sensitive Discord and auto-post settings by default while still saving and activating the complete imported configuration. There is no visible summary or warning that auto-posting is enabled or that a webhook is configured unless the user manually visits the Discord and Auto Post tabs.
This commit changes the settings screen from a single page where all settings were rendered to a tabbed UI that always opens on the Output tab. Sensitive settings such as the main Discord webhook URL, VRChat photo auto-post enablement/webhook, and screenshot auto-post enablement/webhook are now hidden behind separate tabs with no summary or warning on the default tab. An attacker can provide a config.json that enables autoPhoto or screenshotAutoPost and points the webhook to an attacker-controlled Discord webhook. If the user opens that config and clicks Save from the default Output tab, the full hidden config is persisted and saveConfigLocked restarts the auto-photo watchers. Those watchers force Discord upload and use the configured webhook, causing future VRChat photos or screenshots in the watched folders to be sent to the attacker-controlled Discord channel. The backend already supports this functionality, but this commit removes meaningful first-screen visibility for the sensitive imported settings.

# Validation
## Rubric
- [x] Imported/opened config reaches settings mode and the visible tab resets to the non-sensitive Output tab.
- [x] Discord webhook and auto-post enablement/webhook controls are rendered only on non-default tabs, with no Output-tab summary of those hidden fields.
- [x] Saving from settings persists the entire `state.config`, including hidden `autoPhoto` and `screenshotAutoPost` fields.
- [x] Backend save path restarts auto-photo/screenshot watchers when hidden enable flags are true.
- [x] Watcher processing forces Discord upload and uses the configured watcher webhook, enabling future image upload to the attacker-controlled Discord webhook.
## Report
Validated the finding. No crash is expected because this is a logic/UI disclosure issue, not memory corruption. I first attempted a direct debug Go test binary and it reproduced the vulnerable backend behavior without crashing. Valgrind and gdb were attempted but unavailable in the container (`bash: command not found`); an ASan-instrumented Go test was then run successfully.

Evidence:
1. Imported/external configs can enter settings mode: `src/main.go:71-83` loads a `.json` argument into `state.Mode = appcore.ModeSettings`; frontend drag/drop also calls `api.OpenSettings(jsonPaths[0])` then `rememberSettingsBaseline()` at `src/frontend/src/main.js:331-345`.
2. The settings UI defaults/resets to Output: `settingsTab: 'output'` at `src/frontend/src/main.js:31`, and `rememberSettingsBaseline()` resets `this.settingsTab = 'output'` at `src/frontend/src/main.js:174-177`.
3. The sensitive controls are hidden on non-default tabs: tab bar at `src/frontend/src/main.js:845-855`; Output tab is `src/frontend/src/main.js:857-910`; Discord webhook is only rendered when `settingsTab === 'discord'` at `src/frontend/src/main.js:945-957`; auto-post enablement/webhooks are only rendered when `settingsTab === 'autoPost'` at `src/frontend/src/main.js:959-1013`. A targeted visibility script confirmed the Output tab contains none of `autoPhoto`, `screenshotAutoPost`, or `webhookUrl`.
4. Saving persists the whole hidden config: frontend sends `this.state.config` to `api.SaveConfig` at `src/frontend/src/main.js:623-636`; `appcore.SaveConfig` marshals the full config at `src/internal/appcore/config.go:133-142`.
5. Backend activation: `src/app.go:239-248` saves the config and immediately calls `restartAutoPhotoWatcher(cfg)`; `src/app.go:427-475` starts watchers when `cfg.AutoPhoto.Enabled` or `cfg.ScreenshotAutoPost.Enabled` is true.
6. Exfiltration path: `src/internal/appcore/autophoto.go:121-127` forces `cfg.Output.UploadDiscord = true`, copies the watcher webhook into `cfg.Discord.WebhookURL`, and processes the new file. The PoC test set `Output.UploadDiscord=false`, no main Discord webhook, and `AutoPhoto.WebhookURL=https://discord.com/api/webhooks/123/attacker-token`; a mocked HTTP transport captured a POST to `https://discord.com/api/webhooks/123/attacker-token?wait=true` with the image multipart body.

Command evidence:
- `go test -count=1 ./internal/appcore -run 'TestValidation' -v` passed both validation tests.
- `go test -count=1 -asan ./internal/appcore -run 'TestValidation' -v` also passed, reproducing the same behavior under ASan.
- Full app dynamic testing was constrained by missing frontend dist and blocked dependency download, but the backend activation path is directly visible in the cited source lines.

