# Attack-path analysis
Final: high | Decider: model_decided | Matrix severity: medium | Policy adjusted: medium
## Rationale
Kept as high. The issue is in the main runtime product and is reachable through supported config import paths. Static evidence shows attacker-controlled JSON populates full config fields, the UI defaults to Output and hides Discord/Auto Post fields behind non-default tabs, Save persists the full config, and the backend restarts watchers that force Discord upload to the configured webhook. Validation evidence reports a mocked HTTP POST to an attacker webhook under normal backend behavior. Preconditions reduce likelihood to medium, but the impact is significant exfiltration of future local images/screenshots and matches the project threat model's high-severity calibration for silently enabled imported auto-post.
## Likelihood
medium - Exploitation is plausible but not automatic: it requires social engineering the user into opening and saving a config file, and a cautious user could inspect the Discord/Auto Post tabs. There is no internet-exposed endpoint. However, importing local JSON configs is a supported user flow and backend behavior was reproduced by validation tests.
## Impact
high - Successful exploitation can silently enable ongoing outbound posting of future local VRChat photos or screenshots to an attacker-controlled Discord webhook. That is a meaningful privacy/data exfiltration impact, especially for screenshots, though it is limited to new images in configured watched folders and does not provide code execution or full filesystem read.
## Assumptions
- The attacker can persuade a victim to open an attacker-supplied .json configuration file through a supported app flow.
- The victim may save settings from the default Output tab without manually inspecting the Discord or Auto Post tabs.
- The configured webhook is a valid Discord webhook controlled by the attacker.
- After saving, new VRChat photos or screenshots are created in the watched directories.
- victim opens attacker-supplied .json config
- victim clicks Save from settings
- hidden autoPhoto.enabled or screenshotAutoPost.enabled is true
- attacker-controlled Discord webhook URL is valid
- new image appears in the watched folder after watcher initialization
## Path
attacker config.json
  -> supported config import
  -> Output tab shown by default
  -> hidden Discord/Auto Post settings retained
  -> SaveConfig persists full config
  -> watchers restart
  -> new watched image
  -> Discord upload to attacker webhook
## Path evidence
- `src/main.go:71-83` - A single .json CLI argument is loaded as a config and opens the app in settings mode.
- `src/frontend/src/main.js:343-345` - Drag/drop of a single .json calls OpenSettings and then rememberSettingsBaseline.
- `src/frontend/src/main.js:31` - The settings UI default tab is output.
- `src/frontend/src/main.js:174-177` - Every remembered settings baseline resets the visible settings tab to output.
- `src/frontend/src/main.js:845-855` - Tabbed settings navigation provides category buttons but no default sensitive-settings summary.
- `src/frontend/src/main.js:857-910` - The default Output tab is rendered separately from Discord and Auto Post controls.
- `src/frontend/src/main.js:945-957` - The main Discord webhook field is only rendered when settingsTab is discord.
- `src/frontend/src/main.js:959-1013` - Auto-post enablement, watched folders, and auto-post webhook fields are only rendered when settingsTab is autoPost.
- `src/frontend/src/main.js:623-635` - Save sends the full state.config object to SaveConfig or SaveConfigAndProcess, including fields hidden on other tabs.
- `src/internal/appcore/config.go:16-23` - Config includes Discord, AutoPhoto, and ScreenshotAutoPost sections.
- `src/internal/appcore/config.go:115-130` - LoadConfig unmarshals attacker-controlled JSON into the full Config object.
- `src/internal/appcore/config.go:133-142` - SaveConfig marshals and writes the full normalized Config object.
- `src/app.go:239-248` - After saving config, the backend immediately calls restartAutoPhotoWatcher.
- `src/app.go:427-475` - Enabled autoPhoto or screenshotAutoPost settings start background watchers using configured directories and webhook URLs.
- `src/internal/appcore/autophoto.go:39-56` - The watcher initializes seen files, then periodically scans for new watched images.
- `src/internal/appcore/autophoto.go:121-127` - Auto-photo processing forces Discord upload and copies the watcher webhook into the Discord config before processing the image.
- `src/internal/appcore/processor.go:104-116` - When UploadDiscord is true, processing posts the encoded image through UploadDiscordWithContent and stores returned Discord metadata.
- `src/internal/appcore/discord.go:173-200` - Webhook validation restricts the sink to HTTPS discord.com/discordapp.com /api/webhooks/{id}/{token}, mitigating SSRF but not attacker-controlled Discord exfiltration.
## Narrative
The finding is real and reachable. The app intentionally supports opening local .json configs from CLI and drag/drop. Imported configs include Discord webhook, autoPhoto, and screenshotAutoPost fields. The frontend initializes and resets settingsTab to output, while the Discord webhook and auto-post enablement/webhook controls are only rendered on discord and autoPost tabs. Saving sends the entire state.config to the backend. The backend saves the full config and immediately restarts auto-photo/screenshot watchers. Those watchers force Output.UploadDiscord=true, substitute the configured watcher webhook into the Discord config, and process newly detected images, which Processor then uploads to Discord. This is not a network-exposed server issue and requires social engineering plus a Save click, but the impact is meaningful privacy/data exfiltration of future local photos or screenshots to an attacker-controlled Discord channel. Existing controls limit the sink to valid Discord webhook URLs and rate-limit scanning, but they do not address the hidden imported setting activation.
## Controls
- No public listening service or ingress; this is a local desktop application.
- Vue template rendering escapes interpolated values.
- Discord webhook validation requires HTTPS discord.com or discordapp.com /api/webhooks/{id}/{token}.
- Config writes use private file and directory modes in repository code.
- Auto-photo scanning has file and per-tick processing limits.
- Settings tab labels expose that Discord and Auto Post categories exist, but there is no mandatory review or warning on the default tab.
## Blindspots
- Static repository review did not execute the full packaged Wails UI in this environment.
- No live Discord/cloud/API verification was performed; webhook reachability is inferred from source and validation mock evidence.
- Actual Windows ACL behavior for config/history files was not verified.
- The exact user-warning/UX perception in a built application was assessed from source, not from an interactive screen recording.

